error.signature: error: pathspec 'filename' did not match any file(s) known to git

verdict.summary: Git cannot find the specified file or branch. The path may be wrong, case-sensitive, or the file may be untracked/ignored.

dead_ends.action: Using git checkout --force to bypass the error
dead_ends.why_fails: Force flag doesn't create missing files or branches; the pathspec still won't match

workarounds.action: Fetch from remote first, then retry: git fetch --all
workarounds.how:
git fetch --all
git branch -a | grep <branch-name>
# If the branch exists on remote, checkout with tracking:
git checkout -b <branch-name> origin/<branch-name>

workarounds.action: Use git ls-files to find the actual path — it may be case-sensitive
workarounds.how:
# Find tracked files matching a pattern:
git ls-files | grep -i '<filename>'

# On case-insensitive filesystems (macOS, Windows), git may track
# 'README.md' but you typed 'readme.md'. Use the exact case shown by ls-files.
# For branches:
git branch -a | grep -i '<branch-name>'

workarounds.action: Check .gitignore — the file may be excluded from tracking
workarounds.how:
# Check if a file is ignored:
git check-ignore -v <filename>

# If ignored, either remove it from .gitignore or force-add:
git add -f <filename>

# List all ignored files:
git status --ignored

frequently_confused_with.distinction: Both involve pathspec errors. error-pathspec-did-not-match focuses on file paths; pathspec-did-not-match can also refer to branch names in checkout operations.
